and the Format of Deductive Reasoning</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:id>763D2BC4-7FE8-4E5C-9F47-9D87B98A903D</gtr:id><gtr:impact>A talk by an external speaker given to the weekly seminar organised by the project.</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:year>2011</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>Theories in the formal sciences and beyond can be formalized in precise logical languages. Examples are theories of truth, sets, syntax, computability and various theories in metaphysics such as theories of sets.

There are various general results that show that these theories are always incomplete: Certain features of the subject matter cannot be captured by the formal theories. For instance, one would like to have a theory of truth characterizing a onception of truth that is not restricted to a certain domain. Such a truth predicate is used frequently in philosophy, for instance, when philosophers claim that whatever is known is true. However, under fairly general assumptions natural axioms for such a unrestricted notion of truth lead to paradox. In fact, if the conception of truth applies to the domain of semantics
and can be applied to statements about truth, paradoxes arise.

Similarly, if one gives a theory of a formal system, it will not be
possible to prove the consistency of that system within the theory, as G&amp;ouml;del's incompleteness axioms show.

Potentialist accounts of set theory attempt to take seriously the highly compelling thought that there are no limits to which things can be collected as the elements of a set. Without care, this quickly leads to a contradiction, generating Russell's paradox. To make this idea precise, and avoid paradox, a modal framework was developed to axiomatise set theory. This improved on existing potentialist approaches by increasing the expressive power of the language, permitting us to account for more of standard set theory. 

Theories of truth have been devised that allow one to predicate truth in an (almost) unrestricted way. Using truth theories it is also possible to formulate theories that reflect on their soundness, that is, they state, within certain limits, that their consequences are true and that they (or subtheories) are consistent.

In set theory the very notion of indefinite extensibility can be shown to be at the root of modern formulations of set theory. Incorporating indefinite extensibility in a formal theory allows one to recover the usual axiomatizations of set theory and shows how this idea can provide foundations for set theory.

The project yielded also results on the mechanisms behind the
inexpressibility and incompleteness phenomena. It is often thought that sentences that make claims about themselves, so called self-referential sentences, are the source for these phenomena. However, although 'self-reference' is a widely use concept in philosophy, our results shed some light on how elusive this notion is. Even in the precise formal languages self-reference is difficult to capture.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>- The theories of truth developed in the project can be used in other areas of philosophy (epistemology, metaphysics).

- The theories of truth developed in the project can be used in the foundations of mathematics and in set theory.

- The analysis of self-reference should be useful in philosophy, mathematics and linguistics. In particular, it is useful in the analysis of various paradoxes and facilitates the exact formulation of various questions in metamathematics.

- The work on set theory and indefinite extensibility provides an important first step for giving a rigorous account of a &amp;quot;potentialist&amp;quot; picture of the set theoretic hierarchy. This work is highly relevant to the ongoing scholarly debate concerning absolute generality. It also has important applications within the neologicist programme in the philosophy of mathematics. The framework developed also promises to shed new light on difficult questions concerning how mathematical language comes to be interpreted.

- The proof-theoretic analysis can (and have been) be employed for the analysis of various deductive systems in proof theory (in mathematicsand computer science).</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>74023793-0B5F-4920-8764-36E6C5627F06</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Other</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors><gtr:url>http://users.ox.ac.uk/~reflect</gtr:url></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/3CA924E8-910D-4F82-82BB-21FDBFC1C182"><gtr:id>3CA924E8-910D-4F82-82BB-21FDBFC1C182</gtr:id><gtr:title>SELF-REFERENCE IN ARITHMETIC II</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>The Review of Symbolic Logic</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/21a14db672ec512de43aaf44def0fdf0"><gtr:id>21a14db672ec512de43aaf44def0fdf0</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>HALBACH V</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2014-01-01</gtr:date></gtr:publication><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/DB3C14BF-34EF-4605-9CB3-19D9B738F22B"><gtr:id>DB3C14BF-34EF-4605-9CB3-19D9B738F22B</gtr:id><gtr:title>AXIOMATIZING SEMANTIC THEORIES OF TRUTH?</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>The Review of Symbolic Logic</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/7b86df1dcdfbaaaeea126ac415f0a541"><gtr:id>7b86df1dcdfbaaaeea126ac415f0a541</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>FISCHER M</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2015-01-01</gtr:date></gtr:publication><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/D4C117CC-2493-4CC4-AD52-5C7834C79A25"><gtr:id>D4C117CC-2493-4CC4-AD52-5C7834C79A25</gtr:id><gtr:title>Classes and truths in set theory</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Annals of Pure and Applied Logic</gtr:parent